# @ultrawork

**Trigger:** When you want the complete workflow executed at maximum rigor with no shortcuts.

This is `@explore + @deep-interview + @ralplan + @tdd/@ralph + @review + @security-review + @qa + @pipeline + @git-master prep-pr` run as a single coordinated sequence.

## Protocol

1. Call `start_mode` mode=`autopilot` task=`ultrawork: {task}`.
2. Call `save_checkpoint` at the start so you can resume if interrupted.

### Phase 1 — Understand (explore + deep-interview)
3. Run `@explore` to map the relevant subsystem.
4. Score ambiguity. If > 0.3: run `@deep-interview --standard`.
5. Save clarified scope to memory.

### Phase 2 — Plan (ralplan)
6. Run `@ralplan`. Generate plan, present for approval.
7. On approval: `save_plan` approved=true.

### Phase 3 — Execute (tdd or ralph)
8. If building new functionality: use `@tdd` (tests first).
9. If modifying existing code: use `@ralph`.
10. Call `update_mode_state` after each step.

### Phase 4 — Verify (review + security + qa + pipeline)
11. `@review` — full code review, PASS required to continue.
12. `@security-review` — zero CRITICAL required to continue.
13. `@qa --full` — all checks pass.
14. `@pipeline` — full CI gate.

### Phase 5 — Ship (git-master)
15. `@git-master clean-commit` — conventional commit.
16. `@git-master prep-pr` — full PR description.
17. Call `save_checkpoint` with final summary.

## Abort conditions
- `@review` returns FAIL → fix issues before continuing (do not skip)
- `@security-review` returns CRITICAL → fix before continuing (hard stop)
- `@pipeline` FAIL after 2 cycles → surface to user, do not force-ship

## Rules

- No shortcuts. Every phase runs.
- Each phase must pass before the next starts.
- `save_checkpoint` after each phase so ultrawork is resumable.
- This mode is slow by design — use it when quality matters most.
